WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.801 --> 00:00:03.800
MALE SPEAKER: He's the
writer and sole custodian

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:07.590
of the popular blog
ListsOfNote.com.

00:00:07.590 --> 00:00:09.710
And he spent a lot
of time hunting

00:00:09.710 --> 00:00:12.100
down letters that people
have written over the years,

00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:13.820
back when people wrote letters.

00:00:13.820 --> 00:00:16.520
Some people here
remember that at least.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:18.210
I won't embarrass anyone.

00:00:18.210 --> 00:00:21.420
So last night, he comes from
an event in Southern California

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:26.332
with Julia Louis-Dreyfus, BJ
Novak, Dave Eggers, and Thandie

00:00:26.332 --> 00:00:28.290
Newton, who were reading
some of these letters.

00:00:28.290 --> 00:00:30.460
This was a charity event.

00:00:30.460 --> 00:00:32.670
And Sean lives in
Manchester, England,

00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:34.130
with his wife and children.

00:00:34.130 --> 00:00:37.058
So let's give a warm
welcome to Shaun Usher.

00:00:37.058 --> 00:00:40.962
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:41.940 --> 00:00:44.430
So, Shaun, do you want to talk
about the event last night?

00:00:44.430 --> 00:00:46.640
SHAUN USHER: Yeah, so this
is Letters Live, which

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:50.240
is a series of live events that
started when Letters of Note

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:53.340
first came out in the UK.

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:54.270
It's crazy.

00:00:54.270 --> 00:00:57.290
So just famous people, these
really talented performers,

00:00:57.290 --> 00:01:00.530
musicians, authors,
they get up on stage,

00:01:00.530 --> 00:01:03.930
and they read out letters
from this book, as some of you

00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:06.340
are about to do, I think.

00:01:06.340 --> 00:01:08.750
And we've done about
12 of them in the UK.

00:01:08.750 --> 00:01:11.490
And we've had people
like Benedict Cumberbatch

00:01:11.490 --> 00:01:17.630
and Gillian Anderson, Nick Cave,
just these incredible people

00:01:17.630 --> 00:01:20.189
just bringing these
letters to life.

00:01:20.189 --> 00:01:22.230
And it's just been the
most rewarding experience.

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:25.045
So last night, we did the
first one outside of the UK

00:01:25.045 --> 00:01:27.590
and in LA.

00:01:27.590 --> 00:01:30.020
JJ Abrams read a letter.

00:01:30.020 --> 00:01:32.250
Thandie Newton read a
couple, Julia Louis-Dreyfus.

00:01:34.839 --> 00:01:36.380
And it's just the
most amazing night.

00:01:36.380 --> 00:01:37.546
And then I got really drunk.

00:01:37.546 --> 00:01:39.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:39.850 --> 00:01:42.670
And I'm feeling quite
rough at the minute.

00:01:42.670 --> 00:01:45.380
But it's great to be here.

00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:47.310
And this is just
the latest chapter

00:01:47.310 --> 00:01:49.596
of this strange existence.

00:01:52.770 --> 00:01:56.909
MALE SPEAKER: So how did
you start doing this?

00:01:56.909 --> 00:01:58.700
SHAUN USHER: I started
the website in 2009.

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:02.100
But if we go back 13
years when I first

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:06.270
met the lady who is now my
wife, two weeks after we started

00:02:06.270 --> 00:02:08.470
dating, she moved away
to Spain for a year

00:02:08.470 --> 00:02:11.822
as part of a university
course, which

00:02:11.822 --> 00:02:14.030
should be the worst possible
start to a relationship.

00:02:14.030 --> 00:02:17.000
But we decided to keep
in touch by letter.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.390
So we wrote to each
other for 10, 11 months,

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:23.560
and we fell in love by
letter, really sickening.

00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:25.930
But it was the best possible
start we could have had.

00:02:25.930 --> 00:02:27.220
MALE SPEAKER: So none of
those letters are in the book,

00:02:27.220 --> 00:02:27.804
though, right?

00:02:27.804 --> 00:02:30.011
SHAUN USHER: I would never
publish those letters, no.

00:02:30.011 --> 00:02:30.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:32.370
They're terrible.

00:02:32.370 --> 00:02:34.110
But we learned so
much about each other,

00:02:34.110 --> 00:02:36.110
far more than we would
have learned had we

00:02:36.110 --> 00:02:39.830
been face to face, or
particularly communicating

00:02:39.830 --> 00:02:41.262
by email or text message.

00:02:41.262 --> 00:02:43.470
Because when you sit down
to write a letter, at least

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:46.560
with me and my wife
it's certainly the case,

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:48.700
you're far more willing
to be honest and open.

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:50.116
You'd say things
that you wouldn't

00:02:50.116 --> 00:02:52.690
say in any other setting.

00:02:52.690 --> 00:02:54.940
So by the end of that 10
months, we were best friends.

00:02:54.940 --> 00:02:56.150
We'd fallen in love.

00:02:56.150 --> 00:03:00.290
We were set up for life.

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:02.260
So that's when I was
bitten by the bug.

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:05.380
And I knew that I was going
to look into letter writing

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:08.730
as an art form at some point.

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:11.477
And then 2009 I
started the website,

00:03:11.477 --> 00:03:13.310
and it just took off
really, really quickly,

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:14.610
such a simple idea.

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:16.161
The best ideas are.

00:03:16.161 --> 00:03:18.285
I couldn't believe that no
one had done it already.

00:03:20.870 --> 00:03:24.480
And yeah, I didn't really make
much effort to market the blog

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:26.040
or push it out there.

00:03:26.040 --> 00:03:30.600
It did that by itself, thanks
to these amazing letters.

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:35.630
And then 2013, the book came
out after three years of slog.

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:37.990
Making a book like this
is a logistical nightmare,

00:03:37.990 --> 00:03:39.930
because you have to get
so many permissions.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:41.642
It's something
like 300 permission

00:03:41.642 --> 00:03:42.600
we had to get for this.

00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:45.230
And a lot of these people
that wrote these letters

00:03:45.230 --> 00:03:47.530
are now dead, so you have
to deal with their estates,

00:03:47.530 --> 00:03:51.270
and it's an absolute nightmare
getting decisions from people.

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:54.060
So I was so, so
proud of this book.

00:03:54.060 --> 00:03:55.400
It's a beautiful thing.

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:59.584
It's been translated
into 18 languages.

00:03:59.584 --> 00:04:01.000
The appeal of these
letters really

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.110
is universal and the
stories with them.

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:07.410
And just today, I've signed off.

00:04:07.410 --> 00:04:09.910
We've just finished the second
"Letters of Note" book, which

00:04:09.910 --> 00:04:13.690
will be out in the UK at the
end of this year and in the US--

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:15.401
I don't know when.

00:04:15.401 --> 00:04:16.442
FEMALE SPEAKER: In April.

00:04:16.442 --> 00:04:17.233
SHAUN USHER: April.

00:04:17.233 --> 00:04:21.070
Thank you. [CHUCKLES]
So, yeah, my life

00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:23.418
is dedicated to these letters.

00:04:23.418 --> 00:04:25.576
And I couldn't be happier.

00:04:25.576 --> 00:04:26.950
MALE SPEAKER: So
it's interesting

00:04:26.950 --> 00:04:30.500
that you were writing letters
even though the internet was

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:32.930
around then and people
could text or email.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:36.282
But what made you choose not to?

00:04:36.282 --> 00:04:37.490
SHAUN USHER: It was exciting.

00:04:37.490 --> 00:04:38.615
It was something different.

00:04:38.615 --> 00:04:41.670
At this point, and this was
2000 and-- I don't know.

00:04:41.670 --> 00:04:43.400
It was like 13 years ago.

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:45.020
So people were
emailing, obviously,

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:46.920
but not to the extent
that they are now.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:48.970
We weren't using Twitter.

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:51.134
And just the idea of writing
letters to each other

00:04:51.134 --> 00:04:51.675
was romantic.

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:56.060
So we just did,
and it was great.

00:04:56.060 --> 00:04:59.500
And also, when
you email someone,

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:01.180
there's an expectation
that you're

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:04.289
going to reply within a
couple of days at the most.

00:05:04.289 --> 00:05:06.080
If you don't reply
within a couple of days,

00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:06.970
you're deemed rude.

00:05:06.970 --> 00:05:10.665
But with a letter, you
can take anything up

00:05:10.665 --> 00:05:14.560
to like a few weeks to reply,
and it's seemed acceptable.

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:18.100
And during those two weeks,
you can really, really

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:20.430
consider what
you're writing down.

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:25.310
It's a far more considered
form of correspondence.

00:05:25.310 --> 00:05:28.340
And it brings out the best
in people and the worst.

00:05:28.340 --> 00:05:30.430
MALE SPEAKER: Do you
find that other people

00:05:30.430 --> 00:05:32.760
are willing to do
that as well nowadays?

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:34.010
SHAUN USHER: To write letters?

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:35.260
MALE SPEAKER: To
write letters, yeah.

00:05:35.260 --> 00:05:37.570
SHAUN USHER: Well, I'm
probably not the best person

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:41.090
to ask, because I just speak
to people who love letters.

00:05:41.090 --> 00:05:44.230
But since the blog started
and the book came out,

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:47.485
I'm contacted by loads of
people who love letter writing.

00:05:47.485 --> 00:05:50.580
And this has kind of reignited
a passion they once had.

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:54.480
And I get contacted by loads of
teachers saying that they use

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:56.069
this book as a
teaching aid in school

00:05:56.069 --> 00:05:57.860
either to teach about
letter writing itself

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:00.420
or to teach about
historical moments

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:03.980
that we wouldn't know about
were it not for these letters.

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:06.050
Reading letters
by someone who was

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:08.040
in the midst of these
historical events is,

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:12.150
I think, the most enjoyable
way to learn about history

00:06:12.150 --> 00:06:13.820
from the front seat.

00:06:13.820 --> 00:06:15.550
MALE SPEAKER:
Which are your-- we

00:06:15.550 --> 00:06:20.512
have five people, counting me,
who are going to read letters.

00:06:20.512 --> 00:06:22.220
Did you want to bring
them up, or did you

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:24.554
want to talk about some
of your favorites first?

00:06:24.554 --> 00:06:25.470
SHAUN USHER: I'm easy.

00:06:25.470 --> 00:06:26.840
Should I read one out?

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:27.866
MALE SPEAKER: Sure.

00:06:27.866 --> 00:06:29.740
SHAUN USHER: This is
the one I always choose.

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:31.410
It's a bit boring,
really, but this

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:32.660
is one of my favorite letters.

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:33.860
MALE SPEAKER: "I Like
Words," is that the one?

00:06:33.860 --> 00:06:35.240
SHAUN USHER: It's
"I Like Words."

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:36.739
Should I read a
different one, then?

00:06:36.739 --> 00:06:38.569
MALE SPEAKER: No, that's good.

00:06:38.569 --> 00:06:40.360
SHAUN USHER: It's a
job application letter.

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:41.232
This was 1934.

00:06:41.232 --> 00:06:42.690
There's a guy called
Robert Pirosh.

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:44.710
He was a copywriter.

00:06:44.710 --> 00:06:47.230
When I first started Letters
of Note, I was a copywriter.

00:06:47.230 --> 00:06:48.605
So I think that
kind of-- there's

00:06:48.605 --> 00:06:50.700
a parallel there
that attracts me.

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:53.620
So 1934, he wanted to
become a screenwriter.

00:06:53.620 --> 00:06:56.830
So he wrote this standard
form job application letter

00:06:56.830 --> 00:07:00.130
and sent it to all the
movie studios and directors

00:07:00.130 --> 00:07:02.870
he could find addresses for.

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:04.790
And this got him a job with MGM.

00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:06.710
And he went on to
an Academy Award.

00:07:06.710 --> 00:07:08.780
It's the perfect story.

00:07:08.780 --> 00:07:11.460
And standard form job
application letters

00:07:11.460 --> 00:07:15.050
aren't an easy letter to
make sexy, but he's done it.

00:07:15.050 --> 00:07:17.650
And it was so successful.

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:19.910
It's quite compact.

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:23.040
"Dear Sir, I like words.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:25.360
I like fat, buttery
words, such as ooze,

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:27.665
turpitude, gluttonous, toady.

00:07:27.665 --> 00:07:29.780
I like solemn,
angular, creaky words,

00:07:29.780 --> 00:07:32.390
such as straight-laced,
cantankerous, pecunious,

00:07:32.390 --> 00:07:33.720
valedictory.

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:36.680
I like spurious, black-is-white
words, such as mortician,

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:39.380
liquidates,
tonsorial, demimonde.

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:42.140
I like suave, V-words,
such as Svengali,

00:07:42.140 --> 00:07:44.580
svelte, bravura, verve.

00:07:44.580 --> 00:07:48.080
I like crunchy, brittle,
crackly words, such as splinter,

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:50.390
grapple, jostle, crusty.

00:07:50.390 --> 00:07:52.500
I like sullen,
crab-scowling words,

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:56.080
such as skulk,
glower, scabby, churl.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:58.490
I like, oh-heavens,
my-gracious, land's-sake words,

00:07:58.490 --> 00:08:02.190
such as trixie, tucker,
gentile, horrid.

00:08:02.190 --> 00:08:05.200
I like elegant, flowery
words, such as estivates,

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:08.080
peregrinates, elysium, halcyon.

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:12.980
I like wormy, squirmy, mealy
words, such as crawl, blubber,

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:14.610
squeal, drip.

00:08:14.610 --> 00:08:17.800
I like sniggly, chuckling
words, such as cowlick,

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:20.350
gurgle, bubble, and burp.

00:08:20.350 --> 00:08:23.020
I like the word screenwriter
better than copywriter,

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:25.802
so I decided to quit my
job in a New York ad agency

00:08:25.802 --> 00:08:27.010
and try my luck in Hollywood.

00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:29.020
But before taking the
plunge, I went to Europe

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:31.340
for a year of study,
contemplation,

00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:32.600
and horsing around.

00:08:32.600 --> 00:08:35.140
I've just returned,
and I still like words.

00:08:35.140 --> 00:08:37.039
May I have a few with you?

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:38.900
Robert Pirosh."

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:41.390
It's the perfect letter.

00:08:41.390 --> 00:08:42.470
I absolutely adore it.

00:08:42.470 --> 00:08:44.440
MALE SPEAKER: He got quite a
few responses to that, right?

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:44.980
SHAUN USHER: He did, yeah.

00:08:44.980 --> 00:08:47.105
He got quite a few interviews
at different studios,

00:08:47.105 --> 00:08:49.290
and he took a job with MGM.

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:50.580
And the rest is history.

00:08:50.580 --> 00:08:52.780
I found that letter
in a really old book

00:08:52.780 --> 00:08:55.200
that hardly anyone read.

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:59.010
So it was published
in 1970-something.

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:00.180
So yeah, quite a find.

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:04.510
MALE SPEAKER: How
about our readers?

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:04.947
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hi.

00:09:04.947 --> 00:09:05.384
SHAUN USHER: Hi.

00:09:05.384 --> 00:09:06.650
FEMALE SPEAKER: I'm Kate.

00:09:06.650 --> 00:09:11.321
SHAUN USHER: So I was contacted
in 2011, I think it was,

00:09:11.321 --> 00:09:13.320
by a lady who said, I've
got this amazing letter

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:14.350
written by Iggy Pop.

00:09:14.350 --> 00:09:14.940
Do you want to see it?

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:16.856
An I'd seen a couple of
Iggy's letters before,

00:09:16.856 --> 00:09:19.570
and they were great
but nothing special.

00:09:19.570 --> 00:09:22.530
So she sent it to me and said
that, when I was a teenager,

00:09:22.530 --> 00:09:26.210
I was having a terrible time.

00:09:26.210 --> 00:09:27.490
My parents were splitting up.

00:09:27.490 --> 00:09:29.680
We had bailiffs on the door.

00:09:29.680 --> 00:09:30.940
I was really depressed.

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:34.180
I was near the end.

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:36.310
And at the time, Iggy
Pop on one of his albums

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:39.070
had printed his
address on the inlay

00:09:39.070 --> 00:09:41.942
of this album for some
strange reason and said,

00:09:41.942 --> 00:09:43.650
if you want to get in
touch, write to me,

00:09:43.650 --> 00:09:45.716
and I'll try and
get back to you.

00:09:45.716 --> 00:09:48.090
So she wrote to him and said,
I'm having a terrible time.

00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:51.792
And he wrote this amazing,
really lovely letter back.

00:09:51.792 --> 00:09:53.500
FEMALE SPEAKER: "Dear
Laurence, Thank you

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:55.540
for your gorgeous
and charming letter.

00:09:55.540 --> 00:09:57.310
You brighten up my dim life.

00:09:57.310 --> 00:09:59.340
I read the whole
fucking thing, dear.

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:01.620
Of course I'd love to see
you in your black dress

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:03.260
and your white socks, too.

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:05.670
But most of all, I want to
see you take a deep breath

00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:08.470
and do whatever you must to
survive and find something

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:10.320
to be that you can love.

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:13.070
You're obviously a bright
fucking chick with a big heart,

00:10:13.070 --> 00:10:13.640
too.

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:18.610
And I want to issue a belated
happy, happy, happy 21st b-day

00:10:18.610 --> 00:10:20.350
and happy spirit.

00:10:20.350 --> 00:10:24.050
I was miserable and fighting
hard on my 21st b-day, too.

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:25.840
People booed me on
the stage, and I

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:28.800
was staying in someone else's
house, and I was scared.

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:30.320
It's been a long
road since then,

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:32.750
but pressure never
ends in this life.

00:10:32.750 --> 00:10:35.020
Perforation
problems, by the way,

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:38.190
means to me also the holes
that will exist in any story

00:10:38.190 --> 00:10:40.110
we try to make of our lives.

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:41.580
So hang on, my love.

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:45.420
Grow big and strong, and take
your hits and keep going.

00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:48.170
All my love to a really
beautiful girl-- that's you,

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:49.110
Laurence.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:50.734
Iggy Pop."

00:10:50.734 --> 00:10:53.194
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:53.194 --> 00:10:56.150
SHAUN USHER: Thank you.

00:10:56.150 --> 00:10:57.150
It's a lovely letter.

