00:22:44.340 --> 00:22:46.830
from Scott.

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:49.280
SCOTT: Have you found
letters and then

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:53.884
as you worked with them found
them to be fake or hoaxes?

00:22:53.884 --> 00:22:55.050
SHAUN USHER: Not really, no.

00:22:55.050 --> 00:22:56.360
I've been lucky.

00:22:56.360 --> 00:22:57.570
I've been lucky.

00:22:57.570 --> 00:22:58.070
Who knows?

00:22:58.070 --> 00:23:00.486
Maybe there's some letters in
there that aren't actually--

00:23:00.486 --> 00:23:01.602
maybe they are fake.

00:23:01.602 --> 00:23:03.310
But I've not really
come across many, no.

00:23:03.310 --> 00:23:05.589
SCOTT: That's more
of an internet thing.

00:23:05.589 --> 00:23:06.880
SHAUN USHER: Yeah, it is, yeah.

00:23:06.880 --> 00:23:09.854
I do, I take a lot of
time kind of verifying

00:23:09.854 --> 00:23:11.270
the authenticity
of these letters,

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:15.650
because there are so many
fake ones flying around.

00:23:15.650 --> 00:23:20.299
There's one by Stanley
Kubrick in which he supposedly

00:23:20.299 --> 00:23:22.090
writes-- I can't remember
who he writes to,

00:23:22.090 --> 00:23:24.230
but he lets off a lot of steam.

00:23:24.230 --> 00:23:26.540
And that gets
circulated all the time.

00:23:26.540 --> 00:23:32.150
There's another one supposedly
from Sean Connery to Steve

00:23:32.150 --> 00:23:37.220
Jobs, I think it
was, which circulates

00:23:37.220 --> 00:23:38.660
every couple of months.

00:23:38.660 --> 00:23:40.660
And millions of people
probably think it's real.

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:42.118
MALE SPEAKER: That
one's fake, too?

00:23:42.118 --> 00:23:43.660
SHAUN USHER: Yeah,
that's fake, yeah.

00:23:43.660 --> 00:23:45.784
MALE SPEAKER: That was the
Kurt Vonnegut graduation

00:23:45.784 --> 00:23:46.960
speech that never happened?

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:47.910
But I guess that
wasn't a letter.

00:23:47.910 --> 00:23:50.410
But there was a letter from
Kurt Vonnegut in here, right?

00:23:50.410 --> 00:23:50.960
SHAUN USHER: Yeah,
there's one in there.

00:23:50.960 --> 00:23:53.096
There's one in the new
book as well, yeah.

00:23:53.096 --> 00:23:55.470
His collection of letters that
came out a couple of years

00:23:55.470 --> 00:23:58.360
ago is one of the best
books I've ever read.

00:23:58.360 --> 00:24:00.745
STEPHANIE: Are there any
fascinating letters that you

00:24:00.745 --> 00:24:03.060
were like, this should
be read by everybody,

00:24:03.060 --> 00:24:06.580
but the estate has not
agreed to let you publish?

00:24:09.600 --> 00:24:12.620
SHAUN USHER: Yeah, loads.

00:24:12.620 --> 00:24:15.100
STEPHANIE: Tell us about it
even though we can't read them.

00:24:17.660 --> 00:24:20.620
SHAUN USHER: Well, this
isn't really the same thing,

00:24:20.620 --> 00:24:26.290
but there's a Frank Lloyd
Wright letter, the architect.

00:24:26.290 --> 00:24:29.770
A little kid wrote to Frank
Lloyd Wright and said,

00:24:29.770 --> 00:24:31.600
can you build a
house for my dog?

00:24:31.600 --> 00:24:33.480
Can you design a
house for my dog?

00:24:33.480 --> 00:24:37.030
Because Frank Loyd Wright had
built a house for the family

00:24:37.030 --> 00:24:39.480
years and years before.

00:24:39.480 --> 00:24:42.900
And Frank Lloyd Wright wrote
back and said, yes, I'll

00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:43.650
design your house.

00:24:43.650 --> 00:24:44.733
So he designs him a house.

00:24:44.733 --> 00:24:49.570
You can see a photo of
the doghouse in there.

00:24:49.570 --> 00:24:52.639
But in the intro to the letter--
so I applied for permission

00:24:52.639 --> 00:24:53.930
to use the letters in the book.

00:24:53.930 --> 00:24:56.270
And the Frank Lloyd
Wright's estate said,

00:24:56.270 --> 00:24:58.605
you can use it as long as
you take this one line out

00:24:58.605 --> 00:25:02.620
of the intro, which was--
the dog hated the doghouse,

00:25:02.620 --> 00:25:03.765
basically.

00:25:03.765 --> 00:25:04.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:04.600 --> 00:25:06.680
And he refused to
sleep in the doghouse.

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:09.450
And the last line in
the intro originality

00:25:09.450 --> 00:25:14.525
was, the sting in the tail is
the dog hated the doghouse.

00:25:14.525 --> 00:25:16.150
And the Frank Lloyd
Wright estate said,

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:17.870
you've got to take that
out, because we don't--

00:25:17.870 --> 00:25:18.911
MALE SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:18.911 --> 00:25:22.137
SHAUN USHER: It reflects
badly on Frank Lloyd Wright.

00:25:22.137 --> 00:25:23.720
So now whenever I
talk about the book,

00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:26.282
I make a point of telling
everyone about the dog.

00:25:26.282 --> 00:25:28.740
MALE SPEAKER: If any of you
have been to Frank Lloyd Wright

00:25:28.740 --> 00:25:32.390
houses or places like that,
this is a pretty funny picture,

00:25:32.390 --> 00:25:34.794
because it looks just
like one of them. [LAUGHS]

00:25:34.794 --> 00:25:36.710
FEMALE SPEAKER: I'm the
publicist on the book,

00:25:36.710 --> 00:25:40.310
but I do have a question
that has been in my mind.

00:25:40.310 --> 00:25:44.190
So "Letters of Note," letters
are destined for someone else

00:25:44.190 --> 00:25:46.610
to read, but in your new
book "Lists of Note,"

00:25:46.610 --> 00:25:50.210
I'm guessing a lot of those
aren't meant for someone else

00:25:50.210 --> 00:25:51.180
to read.

00:25:51.180 --> 00:25:54.052
So how do you see the
difference between those two?

00:25:55.730 --> 00:25:57.980
SHAUN USHER: Yeah, lists are
definitely more personal,

00:25:57.980 --> 00:25:59.620
I think, than letters.

00:25:59.620 --> 00:26:04.940
But I think they're
less precious.

00:26:04.940 --> 00:26:08.150
I have less-- when I was
making "Letters of Note,"

00:26:08.150 --> 00:26:10.820
I spent a lot of time
wondering whether I

00:26:10.820 --> 00:26:13.330
should publish these letters,
even if I have permission.

00:26:13.330 --> 00:26:16.560
A lot of them are sometimes a
bit too personal to publish.

00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:18.370
But I've never had that
problem with lists.

00:26:18.370 --> 00:26:20.800
I've never stopped and
thought, oh, my God,

00:26:20.800 --> 00:26:24.080
should I publish this?

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:26.665
Although lists are
far more personal,

00:26:26.665 --> 00:26:30.630
they're not as--
does that make sense?

00:26:30.630 --> 00:26:34.135
They're not as
precious I don't think.

00:26:34.135 --> 00:26:35.510
MALE SPEAKER: I
think we're done.

00:26:35.510 --> 00:26:37.930
I'm just going to read
this very short list

00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:42.590
by Preston Sturges of the 11
rules for box office appeal.

00:26:42.590 --> 00:26:44.360
Since this is kind
of box office.

00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:46.950
"Number one, a pretty girl
is better than an ugly one.

00:26:46.950 --> 00:26:49.350
Two, a leg is
better than an arm.

00:26:49.350 --> 00:26:52.340
Three, a bedroom is
better than a living room.

00:26:52.340 --> 00:26:55.730
Four, an arrival is
better than a departure.

00:26:55.730 --> 00:26:57.970
A birth is better than a death.

00:26:57.970 --> 00:27:01.540
A chase is better than a chat.

00:27:01.540 --> 00:27:03.580
A dog is better
than a landscape.

00:27:03.580 --> 00:27:05.940
But a kitten is
better than a dog.

00:27:05.940 --> 00:27:08.280
And a baby is better
than a kitten.

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:10.900
A kiss is better than a baby.

00:27:10.900 --> 00:27:13.460
And a pratfall"-- I'm
not going to do one--

00:27:13.460 --> 00:27:16.460
"is better than anything."

00:27:16.460 --> 00:27:18.870
SHAUN USHER: So when I was
researching "Letters of Note,"

00:27:18.870 --> 00:27:20.744
I was looking through
the archives and papers

00:27:20.744 --> 00:27:22.300
of all these incredible people.

00:27:22.300 --> 00:27:24.500
And I kept finding
lists, amazing lists,

00:27:24.500 --> 00:27:26.190
along with these letters.

00:27:26.190 --> 00:27:28.280
So that's how "Lists
of Note" came about.

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:31.430
And the first one I ever found
was the first list in the book

00:27:31.430 --> 00:27:33.880
is a to-do list by Johnny Cash.

00:27:33.880 --> 00:27:37.320
And he writes all these things
he has to do in the day,

00:27:37.320 --> 00:27:43.460
like drink, eat, go for a
pee, kiss June, his wife, not

00:27:43.460 --> 00:27:45.280
kiss anyone else.

00:27:45.280 --> 00:27:47.709
And then the last thing
is "don't make lists."

00:27:47.709 --> 00:27:49.250
MALE SPEAKER: "Number
one, not smoke.

00:27:49.250 --> 00:27:50.380
Two, Kiss June.

00:27:50.380 --> 00:27:52.640
Three, not Kiss anyone else.

00:27:52.640 --> 00:27:53.960
Four, Cough.

00:27:53.960 --> 00:27:55.480
Pee.

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:56.312
Eat.

00:27:56.312 --> 00:27:57.910
Not eat too much.

00:27:57.910 --> 00:27:59.130
Worry.

00:27:59.130 --> 00:28:00.620
Go see Mama.

00:28:00.620 --> 00:28:02.380
Practice piano.

00:28:02.380 --> 00:28:06.330
And for notes, not write notes."

00:28:06.330 --> 00:28:09.520
With that, let's thank
Shaun for coming.

00:28:09.520 --> 00:28:10.320
[APPLAUSE]

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:10.720
SHAUN USHER: Thank you.

00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:11.550
MALE SPEAKER: We
have books for sale,

00:28:11.550 --> 00:28:13.049
and he'll be available
to sign them.

00:28:13.049 --> 00:28:15.220
Thanks for coming, everybody.

